N2  - Thailand is now the largest exporter of natural rubber with one third of the volume traded annually (3.252 million tons produced and 2.866 million tons exported in 2010). Beyond the quantitative performance, Thailand is distinguished by the origin of this production, because 95% of plantations are owned by family farms. Much of the transformation is further ensured by small farmer cooperatives. Currently, nearly 10% of the Thai population lives on production, trade and processing of natural rubber. Based on a literature review supplemented by some interviews with resource persons, this paper analyzes the factors behind this remarkable development of the smallholder rubber plantations in Thailand. This performance is certainly attributable to population dynamics, various forms of information flow but also and above all, it seems the result of a public policy commitment for nearly 50 years. The main factors of quantitative and qualitative development of natural rubber plantations, detailed in this paper, have been the result of long term public measures concerning different levels of the sector. In addition, much of this development was funded by the industry itself, by a para-fiscal levy on exported volumes of natural rubber. In addition to a remarkable agricultural intensification, which mainly concerns areas of historical emergence of the rubber production in Thailand, the state has also encouraged the geographical expansion of rubber plantations in the northern regions of the country. In this context less favorable in terms of soil and climate conditions, the adoption of the rubber production is still relatively low but it has enjoyed remarkable growth in recent years. In high production regions of natural rubber in southern Thailand, the dependence of farmers' income on rubber is very important. Pursuing an objective of fighting against poverty, the State is also ready, as it did in 2009, to intervene on stocks to regulate prices when registering excessively downward. In doing so, the State helps to maintain the scope of this production.
